  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research article titled \"Divergent genetic landscapes drive lower levels of AmpC induction and stable de-repression in <i>Serratia marcescens</i> compared to <i>Enterobacter cloacae</i>\" has garnered attention in the field of antimicrobial resistance, evidenced by its citations across various reputable journals. Supported by significant funding from renowned institutions, this work contributes to our understanding of genetic factors influencing antibiotic resistance mechanisms.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article, published in the prestigious journal <i>Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy</i>, presents an insightful comparison of the genetic landscapes of <i>Serratia marcescens</i> and <i>Enterobacter cloacae</i>. The findings reveal that the former exhibits lower levels of AmpC induction, coupled with stable de-repression, potentially influencing treatment efficacy and clinical outcomes. This research is particularly significant in the current landscape of rising antibiotic resistance.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study is underpinned by the strong institutional backing of key institutions such as Brigham and Women's Hospital and Harvard University. This affiliation not only adds credibility but also ensures that the work is situated within a rich scientific environment where similar research is actively pursued. Notably, the authors acknowledge the substantial support from funding agencies such as the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, emphasizing the institutional investment in exploring critical issues surrounding antimicrobial resistance.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Citations indicate that this work is making waves in the academic community, with a total of eight citations recorded on OpenAlex. Significant citations have emerged from leading journals, including the <i>Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy</i> and <i>BMC Microbiology</i>, suggesting that this research is being recognized and utilized by other scientists in the field. Such robust citation activity reflects the relevance and potential influence of the findings on future research directions.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, the study highlights critical insights into the genetic mechanisms of antibiotic resistance while receiving robust academic recognition and support from notable funding agencies. The integration of this research within the broader discourse of antimicrobial resistance positions it as substantial to the ongoing efforts aimed at combating bacterial infections and improving therapeutic strategies.</p>",
